# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baltimore-orioles
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The **1894 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1894.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 30, with the Baltimore Orioles as the pennant winner of the National League and the New York Giants as runner-up.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first Temple Cup on October 4 and ended with Game 4 on October 8.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants swept the Orioles, capturing their first Temple Cup.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the Temple Cup, following the end of the World's Championship Series with the demise of the American Association in 1891 and the one-off, split-season 1892 World's Championship Series.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The 1894 schedule consisted of 132 games for the twelve teams of the National League.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other eleven teams in the league.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place in the previous season and would be used until 1898.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring eight teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on September 30, also featuring eight teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The Temple Cup took place between October 4 and October 8.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Makeshift stands built for remainder of the season, from August 18.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the start of the season, the Cincinnati Reds' home as League Park saw major changes.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] A new grandstand in what was left field was built, as well as an ampitheater.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1894-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball diamond was shifted from the southeast corner of the lot to the southwest corner, with the original seating retained as right field seating.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1901 Milwaukee Brewers** were an American professional baseball team.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] This was the final season of the Milwaukee Brewers team that operated from 1894 to 1901, one of multiple teams in Milwaukee's professional baseball history to use the Brewers nickname, and the only season the team competed at the major-league level.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished eighth in the inaugural season of the American League with a record of 48 wins and 89 losses, 35+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] After the season, the major-league franchise relocated and became the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] Louis Browns, where they remained through the 1953 season, after which the franchise again relocated and became the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] A franchise in the minor-league American Association played in Milwaukee from 1902 through 1952 using the Milwaukee Brewers name.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] 4/25/01: In the first game of the season in Detroit, the Brewers held a 13–4 lead going into the ninth inning.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Detroit Tigers scored 10 runs in the bottom of the inning to win, a record which still stands as the greatest ninth inning comeback in major league baseball history.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The **1902 major league baseball season** was contested from April 17 through October 5, 1902.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American League (AL), with the Philadelphia Athletics winning the AL pennant.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant for the second consecutive season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Milwaukee Brewers moved and became the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns; the franchise would remain in St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Louis through 1953, and in 1954 moved again to become the modern Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This season would be the last of this season's Baltimore Orioles, who would fold following the conclusion of the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues renamed as the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The 1902 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with every team playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 19, with a one-off game between the Baltimore Orioles and the Boston Americans, with the rest of the season beginning April 23.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 29, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 5.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (8 in AL, 15 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] Across both leagues, Sammy Strang tied as a leader in runs at 109 (108 with the Chicago White Stockings of the AL and 1 with the Chicago Orphans of the NL).
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds leave League Park (where they played for 18 seasons) and move to the Palace of the Fans, where they would go on to play for ten seasons through 1911.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the first for the franchise in St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 78 wins and 58 losses.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The Milwaukee Brewers of the American League decided to relocate to St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Ownership chose the name "Browns" on purpose, as the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns had won American Association titles from 1885 to 1889.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] That team moved to the National League in 1892, became the Perfectos in 1899, and has been known as the Cardinals since 1900.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The new Browns quickly tried to align itself with fans by raiding the rival Cardinals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] A couple of Cardinals players were signed, including slick fielding future Hall of Fame shortstop Bobby Wallace and 1901 National League batting champion outfielder Jesse Burkett.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1902-st-louis-browns-season] While playing as the 1901 Brewers, the team had a record of 48–89 (.350) and finished in eighth place, while the 1902 Browns played to a record of 78–58 (.574) and finished in second place.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1903-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1903-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished sixth in the American League with a record of 65 wins and 74 losses, 26½ games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:baltimore-orioles/1904-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished sixth in the American League with a record of 65 wins and 87 losses, 29 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The **Baltimore Orioles** are an American professional baseball team based in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles compete in Major League Baseball (MLB) as a member club of the American League (AL) East Division.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] As one of the American League's eight charter teams in 1901, the franchise spent its first year as a major league club in Milwaukee as the Milwaukee Brewers before moving to St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis, the franchise was purchased in 1953 by a syndicate of Baltimore business and civic interests, led by attorney and civic activist Clarence Miles and Mayor Thomas D'Alesandro Jr.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The team's current owner is David Rubenstein.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' home ballpark is Oriole Park at Camden Yards, which opened in 1992 in downtown Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The oriole is the official state bird of Maryland; the name has been used by several baseball clubs in the city, including another AL charter member franchise which folded after the 1902 season and was replaced the next year by the New York Highlanders, later the Yankees.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Nicknames for the team include the "**O's**" and the "**Birds**".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The franchise's first World Series appearance came in 1944 when the Browns lost to the St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles went on to make six World Series appearances from 1966 to 1983, winning three in 1966, 1970, and 1983.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] This era of the club featured several future Hall of Famers who would later be inducted representing the Orioles, such as third baseman Brooks Robinson, outfielder Frank Robinson, starting pitcher Jim Palmer, first baseman Eddie Murray, shortstop Cal Ripken Jr., and manager Earl Weaver.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The franchise was the last charter member of the American League to win a pennant, and the last charter member to win a World Series.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since their last World Series appearance in 1983, the Orioles have struggled to sustain success, including suffering 14 consecutive losing seasons between 1998 and 2011.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In the 2010s, the team qualified for the postseason three times under manager Buck Showalter and general manager Dan Duquette, including a division title and advancement to the American League Championship Series for the first time in 17 years in 2014.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] However, the 2018 season saw the Orioles lose 115 games, the most in franchise history.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Two years after finishing 52–110 in 2021, the Orioles went 101–61 in 2023, en route to winning the AL East for the first time since 2014.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' current manager is Craig Albernaz, while Mike Elias serves as general manager and executive vice president.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since moving to Baltimore in 1954, the Orioles have an overall win–loss record of 5,733–5,617–12 (.505) through the end of 2025.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles franchise can trace its roots back to the original Milwaukee Brewers of the Western League (WL), beginning in 1894 when the league reorganized.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Brewers were still league members when the WL renamed itself the American League (AL) in 1900.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] At the end of the 1900 season, the AL removed itself from baseball's National Agreement, the formal understanding between the National League (NL) and the minor leagues, and declared itself a competing major league.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] During 1901, the first season the AL operated as a major league, the Brewers finished last among the league's eight teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis and became the "Browns", named after the original name of the 1880s club now known as the Cardinals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Although they usually fielded mediocre teams, they were very popular at the gate.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 1916, after years of prosperity at the gate, Robert Hedges sold the team to Phil Ball, who made a considerable effort to make the Browns competitive.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] However, Ball's tenure was marked by errors, including the firing of Branch Rickey, which eventually benefited the Cardinals, who shared Sportsman's Park with the Browns.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The 1944 season saw the Browns winning their only St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis-based American League pennant, becoming the last of the 16 teams that made up the major leagues from 1901 to 1960, to play in a World Series.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 1951, Bill Veeck purchased the Browns and introduced a series of promotions and wild antics.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Veeck's efforts to drive the Cardinals out of St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis failed when Anheuser-Busch purchased the Cardinals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Veeck attempted to move the Browns to Milwaukee and then Baltimore, but both moves were initially blocked by other American League owners.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Eventually, Veeck sold his stake to a group of Baltimore investors, and the team moved to Baltimore for the 1954 season, renaming themselves the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The name has a rich history in Baltimore, having been used by Baltimore baseball teams since the late 19th century.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' early years in Baltimore were marked by a gradual climb to respectability, leading to their first World Series title in 1966.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles enjoyed a period of sustained success from 1966 to 1983, winning three World Series titles and six American League pennants.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] After the 1983 World Series win, the Orioles experienced a decline, culminating in the 1988 season where they lost the first 21 games.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 1989, the Orioles showed improvement with the "Why Not?" Orioles finishing second in the AL East.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The opening of Oriole Park at Camden Yards in 1992 marked a new era, and the team returned to the playoffs in 1996 and 1997.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] However, the late 1990s and 2000s were characterized by losing seasons and rebuilding efforts.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles saw a resurgence in the 2010s, making the playoffs in 2012, 2014, and 2016, with Buck Showalter as manager.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The team struggled again towards the end of the decade, leading to a major rebuild.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The 2020s have been marked by rebuilding efforts and developing young talent, aiming for future competitiveness.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2022, anticipated first-round pick catcher Adley Rutschman made his major-league debut in addition to rookie closer Félix Bautista.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles finished the 2022 season with a 83–79 record, becoming the second team in MLB history to have a winning season only one year after losing 110 or more games.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] On June 9, 2022, Louis Angelos sued his brother, Orioles chairman and CEO John P.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Angelos, and mother Georgia Angelos in Baltimore County Circuit Court.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis Angelos claims that their father intended for the brothers and their mother to share control of the team.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The lawsuit states the elder Angelos collapsed in 2017 due to heart problems and established a trust with his wife and sons as co-trustees.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis Angelos is seeking to have his brother and mother removed as co-trustees of the trust that controls the Orioles and removed as co-agents of Peter Angelos' power of attorney.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The suit claims Georgia Angelos wants to sell the team and an advisor attempted to negotiate a sale in 2020 but John Angelos vetoed a potential deal.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The suit claims Angelos unilaterally fired long-time employees loyal to his father, including former center fielder Brady Anderson, the longtime special assistant to the executive vice president for baseball operations.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The suit claims John Angelos transferred tens of millions of dollars' worth of property out of his father's law firm and into a limited liability company controlled by his personal attorney.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In separate statements released by the team, Georgia and John Angelos refuted the claims.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In the event of any sale, Major League Baseball has reportedly encouraged Cal Ripken Jr to be part of any incoming ownership group that may take control of the team.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In April 2023, the Orioles went 19–9, setting a franchise record for wins in the month of April.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] During a "seemingly benign" introduction to a game against the Tampa Bay Rays, Brown observed that the team had not won a series at Tropicana Field in the past several seasons.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] It was described in *The Athletic* as a "petty" move by John Angelos, "the only person [in the organization] with enough power that no one dare question the validity of anything he says and does, no matter how foolish it is." Several broadcasters came to Brown's defense after the news broke.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In May 2023, following the team's new water-themed celebrations, Camden Yards created a Bird Bath splash zone in left field, where fans in one section had the opportunity get sprayed by the water hose-wielding "Mr.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Splash" following an Orioles extra base hit.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles finished the 2023 season with a record of 101–61, winning the American League East division for the first time since 2014, and claiming their first 100+ win season since 1980.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] On July 30, the pitching staff of Dean Kremer, Mike Baumann, Shintaro Fujinami, Danny Coulombe, and Yennier Canó combined to set a franchise record for the most strikeouts in a 9-inning game against the Yankees.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The 2023 pitching staff also broke the Orioles franchise record of single-season strikeouts on September 6.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] However, the team's successful season ended in the postseason American League Division Series, with the Orioles losing three straight games to the Texas Rangers.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The series sweep was the first time since the 2022 season that the Orioles had been swept in a series.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Manager Brandon Hyde was awarded 2023 AL Manager of the Year, and players Adley Rutschman and Gunnar Henderson both were awarded the Silver Slugger Award.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Additionally, Henderson was voted unanimous AL Rookie of the Year, marking the first time the team had a ROY winner since Gregg Olson in 1989.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In January 2024, John Angelos reached a $1.7 billion deal to sell the Orioles to a group led by David Rubenstein, a Baltimore native and founder of The Carlyle Group.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The group includes Cal Ripken, New York investment manager Michael Arougheti, former Baltimore mayor Kurt Schmoke, businessman Michael Bloomberg and NBA hall of famer Grant Hill.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] For tax reasons, the group would acquire 40% of the team with the Angelos family selling the remainder of Peter Angelos' stake after his death.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The deal includes the Orioles' majority stake in MASN.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Peter Angelos died aged 94 on March 23, 2024; his death occurred four days before the sale of the Orioles was finalized.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] On August 1, 2024, the Orioles' majority ownership group led by private equity billionaire David Rubenstein took full control of the team, when a deal closed for the group to purchase the remainder of the organization.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' home uniform is white with the word "Orioles" written across the chest.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The road uniform is gray with the word "Baltimore" written across the chest.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] After several decades, approximately 20% of the team's attendance came from the metro Washington area.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2013, ESPN ran a "Battle of the Uniforms" contest between all 30 Major League clubs.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Despite using a ranking system that had the Orioles as a #13 seed, the Birds beat the #1 seed Cardinals in the championship round.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' cap design have alternated between the team's iconic "cartoon bird" logo and the full-bodied bird logo.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Initially, the caps had the full-bodied bird logo between 1954 and 1965, alternating between an all-black cap and an orange-brimmed black cap.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] They also wore a black cap with an orange block-letter "B" for part of the 1963 season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The "cartoon bird" was first used in 1966, and with minor tweaks, was prominently featured on the team's caps until 1988.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Initially, the Orioles kept the orange-brimmed black cap with the "cartoon bird" but switched to a white-paneled black cap with orange brim in 1975.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Also that same year, they wore orange-paneled black caps to pair with the orange alternates, but these lasted only two seasons.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 1989, the full-bodied bird logo returned along with the all-black cap, with a few tweaks along the way.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Initially the cap was used regardless of home or road games, but in 2002 the caps were worn only on the road until 2008.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] An orange-brimmed variety was also introduced in 1995.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Initially exclusive to the team's black uniforms, this style became the home cap in 2002 and became the team's regular cap (home or away) from 2009 to 2011.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2012, the Orioles brought back a modernized version of the "cartoon bird" along with the white-paneled and orange-brimmed black cap for home games and the orange-brimmed black cap for road games.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The script "O's" cap, introduced in 2005, is a black cap with orange brim and is typically worn with the black alternate uniform.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] New for 2026 is a similarly designed "B" cap, similar to the "O's" cap but with the script "B" from their road uniform.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] For games with the "City Connect" uniform, the Orioles wear a dark green cap with cream panel and orange brim featuring a stylized orange "B" in front; the previous version featured a black cap with the white script "B" in front.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] An alternate uniform is black with the word "Orioles" written across the chest.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] They first wore black uniforms in the 1993 season and continue to do so since; the current style with the letters lacking additional trim was first used in 2000.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles wear their black alternate jerseys for Friday night games with the alternate "O's" cap (first introduced in 2005), whether at home or on the road; the regular batting helmet is still used with this uniform.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2017, the Orioles began to use their batting practice caps for select games with the black uniforms.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The aforementioned caps resemble their regular road caps save for the black bill.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Occasionally, the Orioles would also wear the black alternates on other days of the week, often pairing them with the home or road "cartoon bird" caps.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] After the "City Connect" uniforms became the team's Friday home uniform (see below), the black alternates were only used on Friday road games and on home games depending on the preference of the starting pitcher.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles also wore orange alternate uniforms at various points in their history.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The orange alternates were first used in the 1971 season and were paired with orange pants, but these lasted only two seasons.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The second orange uniform, which was a pullover style, was worn from 1975 to 1987, but were not worn at all in the 1983, 1985 and 1986 seasons.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] A third orange uniform was used from 1988 to 1992, returning to the button-down style.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2012, the Orioles brought back the orange uniforms as a second alternate uniform; the team currently wears them on Saturdays at home or on the road, though they've also worn them on other days of the week either due to pitcher's preference or a previously postponed contest.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] For 2025, the Orioles brought back the all-orange alternate for select games, while keeping the orange uniform/white pants option for a few other games.; the all-orange alternate is always worn with the road "cartoon bird" cap in a similar manner to its previous incarnation.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2023, the Orioles introduced a City Connect uniform, inspired by the art and culture of Baltimore and its neighborhoods.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The uniform is mostly black base from the jersey to pants.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Across the chest, it features the city name "BALTIMORE" in white lettering, and on the collar and sleeves features a small batch of colors and shapes, representing the neighborhoods of Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The cap, which is also on a black base, features an italic white "B".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2024, the City Connect uniform was worn with the home white pants for select games.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Their second City Connect uniform, unveiled in 2026, is a cream base with dark green and orange sleeves, and paid homage to Oriole Park at Camden Yards.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The chest featured the shortened nickname "BMORE" in dark green block letters with cream trim and orange drop shadows; atop the "R" is the Orioles' realistic bird crest prominently seen on their caps during the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] A sleeve patch inspired by the Eutaw Street home run plaques featured the full team along with the phrase "FROM THE STOOP TO THE YARDS" in an allusion to the city's beloved stoops on houses.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The "410" sign below is the main area code of Maryland.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Caps are in dark green with white panels and orange brim, and includes a stylized orange "B" as a nod to the original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles announced its first-ever jersey sponsorship deal with T.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] A circular dark blue, aqua and white sleeve patch with the investment management firm's bighorn sheep logo debuted in a home game against the Atlanta Braves the following night on June 11.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In Baltimore, Orioles radio broadcasts can be heard on WBAL-AM and WIYY, both owned by Hearst Television.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Geoff Arnold, Melanie Newman, Brett Hollander, Scott Garceau and Kevin Brown alternate as play-by-play announcers.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] WBAL feeds the games to a network of 36 stations, covering Washington, D.C., and all or portions of Maryland, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Virginia, West Virginia, and North Carolina.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] This is WBAL's fourth stint as the Orioles flagship.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] WBAL has carried Orioles games for most of the team's time in Baltimore.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Prior to WBAL and WIYY, Orioles games were broadcast locally on WJZ-FM from 2015 to 2021.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] WJZ had earlier carried broadcasts from 2007 to 2010.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Six former Orioles franchise radio announcers have received the Hall of Fame's Ford C.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Frick Award for excellence in broadcasting: Chuck Thompson (who was also the voice of the old NFL Baltimore Colts); Jon Miller (now with the San Francisco Giants); Ernie Harwell, Herb Carneal; Bob Murphy and Harry Caray (as a St.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 1991, the Orioles experimented with longtime TV writer/producer Ken Levine as a play-by-play broadcaster.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Levine was best noted for his work on TV shows such as *Cheers* and *M*A*S*H*, but lasted only one season in the Orioles broadcast booth.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] MASN, co-owned by the Orioles and the Washington Nationals, is the team's exclusive television broadcaster.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] MASN airs almost the entire slate of regular season games.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Some exceptions include Friday Night Baseball on Apple TV, Saturday games on either Fox (via its Baltimore affiliate, WBFF) or Fox Sports 1, select weekday games on ESPN, or Sunday games on NBC (via its Balitmore affiliate, WBAL-TV) and Peacock.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Many MASN telecasts in conflict with Nationals' game telecasts air on an alternate MASN2 feed.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Veteran sportscaster Gary Thorne served as lead television announcer from 2007 to 2019, with Jim Hunter as his backup along with Hall of Fame member and former Orioles pitcher Jim Palmer and former Oriole infielder Mike Bordick as color analysts, who almost always work separately.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2020, Thorne and Palmer were removed from the television booth due to COVID-19 concerns and replaced with Scott Garceau.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In 2021, MASN let go Thorne, Hunter, analysts Mike Bordick and Rick Dempsey, and studio host Tom Davis, and added Ben McDonald as a secondary analyst.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Starting in 2022, Kevin Brown became the primary TV play-by-play announcer, with Garceau, Arnold or Newman the backups.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles severed their ties with Comcast SportsNet Mid-Atlantic (currently Monumental Sports Network under Ted Leonsis) at the end of the 2006 season in favor of MASN, a joint venture with the Washington Nationals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] It had been the Orioles' cable partner since 1984, when it was known as Home Team Sports.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles and the Washington Nationals have been in a dispute since the early 2010s, MASN is owned by both teams with the Orioles holding an 80% stake.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The dispute which is ongoing as of October 2020 contends that the Nationals deserves a greater fee from MASN due to the team's recent success and market growth.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] When fees paid to each team were first negotiated, both teams were paid the same fees.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] WJZ-TV was the Orioles' broadcast TV home, completing its latest stint from 1994 through 2017.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since MASN acquired rights in 2007, its coverage was simulcast on WJZ-TV under the branding "MASN on WJZ 13".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] MASN elected not to syndicate any Orioles or Washington Nationals games to broadcast television for the 2018 season, marking the first time since the Orioles' arrival that their games are not on local broadcast television.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Previously, WJZ-TV carried the team from their arrival in Baltimore in 1954 through 1978.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In the first four seasons, WJZ-TV shared coverage with Baltimore's other two stations, WMAR-TV and WBAL-TV.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The games moved to WMAR from 1979 through 1993 before returning to WJZ-TV.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] From 1994 to 2009, some Orioles games aired on WNUV.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since its introduction at games by the "Roar from 34", led by Wild Bill Hagy and others, in the late 1970s, it has been a tradition at Orioles games for fans to yell out the "Oh" in the line "Oh, say does that Star-Spangled Banner yet wave" in "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] "The Star-Spangled Banner" has special meaning to Baltimore historically, as it was written during the Battle of Baltimore in the War of 1812 by Francis Scott Key, a Baltimorean.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The tradition is often carried out at other sporting events, both professional and amateur, and even sometimes at non-sporting events where the anthem is played, throughout the Baltimore/Washington area and beyond.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Fans in Norfolk, Virginia, chanted "O!" even before the Tides became an Orioles affiliate.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The practice caught some attention in the spring of 2005, when fans performed the "O!" cry at Washington Nationals games at RFK Stadium.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The "O!" chant is also common at sporting events for the various Maryland Terrapins teams at the University of Maryland, College Park.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] At Cal Ripken Jr.'s induction into the National Baseball Hall of Fame, the crowd, composed mostly of Orioles fans, carried out the "O!" tradition during Tony Gwynn's daughter's rendition of "The Star-Spangled Banner".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Additionally, a faint but audible "O!" could be heard on the television broadcast of Barack Obama's pre-inaugural visit to Baltimore as the national anthem played before his entrance.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] A resounding "O!" bellowed from the nearly 30,000 Ravens fans who attended the November 21, 2010, away game at the Carolina Panthers' Bank of America Stadium in Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] A similar loud "O!" was heard from fans attending Super Bowl XLVII between the Baltimore Ravens and the San Francisco 49ers.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The "O!" chant was also heard during the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, when Baltimore native Michael Phelps received his gold medal for the 4 × 200 m freestyle on August 9, 2016.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In recent years, when the Orioles host the Toronto Blue Jays, fans have begun to shout out the multiple instances of the word "O" in "O Canada".
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Washington Capitals fans will do the same when they play one of the NHL's Canadian teams.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since August 1975, it has been an Orioles tradition to play John Denver's "Thank God I'm a Country Boy" during the seventh-inning stretch.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The song was tremendously successful nationwide, topping the Billboard Top 100 for a week, and was played in stadiums across the country.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles were chasing the Red Sox for the American League East Division title and incorporated numerous "good luck charms." After an inspiring comeback win, Oriole staff began playing this song at the seventh inning stretch of every home game as one of the good-luck charms.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] During a nationally televised game on September 20, 1997, Denver himself danced to the song atop the Orioles' dugout, one of his final public appearances before dying in a plane crash three weeks later.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Beginning in the 1999 season, Charlie Zill, then an usher, would put on overalls, a straw hat, and false teeth and dance around the club-level section (244) that he tended to.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] He went by the name Zillbilly and had an orange violin to spin for the fiddle solos.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Zill performed the skit until shortly before he died in early 2013.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Songs from notable games in the team's history include "One Moment in Time" for Cal Ripken's record-breaking game in 1995, as well as the theme from *Pearl Harbor*, "There You'll Be" by Faith Hill, during his final game in 2001.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The theme from *Field of Dreams* was played at the last game at Memorial Stadium in 1991, and the song "Magic to Do" from the stage musical *Pippin* was used that season to commemorate "Orioles Magic" on 33rd Street.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] During the Orioles' heyday in the 1970s, a club song, appropriately titled "Orioles Magic (Feel It Happen)", was composed by Walt Woodward, and played when the team ran out until Opening Day of 2008.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Since then, the song (a favorite among all fans, who appreciated its references to Wild Bill Hagy and Earl Weaver) is played (along with a video featuring several Orioles stars performing the song) only after wins.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In the 2010s, "Seven Nation Army" was often played as a hype song while the fans chant the signature bass riff as a rally cry during key moments of a game or after a walk-off hit.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] In the 2023 season, closer Felix Bautista would come out of the bullpen to the ominous whistle of *The Wire* character Omar Little.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The United States Army Field Band from Fort Meade performs the national anthem before the Orioles' final home game of the season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Band has also played the anthem at the finales of three World Series in which the Orioles played: 1970, 1971 and 1979.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] They are introduced as the "First Army Band" during the pregame ceremonies.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] For 23 years, Rex Barney was the PA announcer for the Orioles.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] His voice became a fixture of both Memorial Stadium and Camden Yards, and his expression "Give that fan a contract", uttered whenever a fan caught a foul ball, was one of his trademarks – the other being his distinct "Thank Yooooou ..." following every announcement.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] (He was also known on occasion to say "Give that fan an error" after a dropped foul ball.) Barney died on August 12, 1997, and in his honor that night's game at Camden Yards against the Oakland Athletics was held without a public–address announcer.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Barney was replaced as Camden Yards' PA Announcer by Dave McGowan, who held the position from 1998 to 2011, after Chris Ely finished out the 1997 season.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Lifelong Orioles fan and former MLB Fan Cave resident Ryan Wagner soon took over as the PA announcer.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] He was chosen out of a field of more than 670 applicants in the 2011–12 offseason.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] He was dismissed just hours before the team's 2021 home opener, reportedly because of his conduct on Twitter.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Adrienne Roberson, at the time the public address announcer for the Bowie Baysox and Wagner's primary substitute, has been the team's announcer from 2021 onward.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] She became the second woman to be named an MLB team's primary PA announcer, following Renel Brooks-Moon of the San Francisco Giants.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Of the eight original American League teams, the Orioles were the last of the eight to win the World Series, doing so in 1966 with its four–game sweep of the heavily favored Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Louis Browns, they played in only one World Series, the 1944 matchup against their Sportsman's Park tenants, the Cardinals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles won the first-ever American League Championship Series in 1969, and in 2012 the Orioles beat the Texas Rangers in the inaugural American League Wild Card game, where for the first time two Wild Card teams faced each other during postseason play.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles will retire a number only when a player has been inducted into the Hall of Fame with Cal Ripken Jr. being the only exception.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] However, the Orioles have placed moratoriums on other former Orioles' numbers following their deaths (see note below).
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles' official team hall of fame is located on display on Eutaw Street at Camden Yards.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Baltimore Orioles farm system consists of seven minor league affiliates.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] The Orioles have a minor regional rivalry with the nearby Washington Nationals nicknamed the Beltway Series or Battle of the Beltways.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] Baltimore currently leads the series with a 55–39 record over the Nationals.
[src:baltimore-orioles/baltimore-orioles] They have divisional rivals within the American League East, predominately with the New York Yankees in the past and in more recent years with the Toronto Blue Jays.
